english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of the Lay Buddhist Dongang居士 Lee
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mencius, in his discourse on choosing worthies as companions, said: "Recite his poems, read his writings—if you do not know the man, how can this suffice? Thus we must examine his age." I have long maintained that in critiquing literature, one must proceed in like manner. Literature is the quintessence of human speech. Yet speech does not necessarily align with the heart, nor does it always reflect the truth of one's deeds and conduct. The writings of Sima Xiangru and Yang Xiong of Han, of Liu Zongyuan of Tang, of Wang Anshi of Song—their words spread across the page beyond reproach. Yet when one carefully examines the actual substance of their conduct, one cannot but voice reservations. Consider a butcher who venerates Buddha, or a courtesan who studies propriety—from outward appearance they seem proper, but tracing to their roots, they remain butcher and courtesan still. How can such contradiction be concealed? This is why we must recite the poems and read the writings, but more urgently still, examine the age in which he lived.

    I, Saek, am unschooled—how dare I judge the ancients? How dare I judge the scholars of the realm? Yet since I cannot esteem a man by his writings alone, I cannot remain silent. The late Minister of密直 and Chief Censor Lee, intent on carving his predecessor Dongang居士's collected works into wood blocks, through his son-in-law, the Minister of War安君, has requested my preface. I have long admired the Lay Buddhist's lofty character, and have regretted not being born in his time, so that I might take up the whip and follow in his wake. To have my name inscribed at the head of his work is a fortune beyond measure—how could I refuse?

    Let me examine the facts: The Lay Buddhist, from youth devoted to learning, labored mightily to establish himself. When the court returned in the year Gyeongoh, though still of humble station, through his remonstrance he gained the favor of King Chunggyeong. Following Minister순安 into the Yuan court, whenever imperial favor was bestowed, he would present memorials of gratitude, and his words struck all who heard them with wonder. His reputation spread far. Serving King Chungnyeol as Remonstrator, he grew ever more passionate in his counsel, yet finding it unheeded, he withdrew into the depths of Dutasan Mountain, as if to spend his life there. When King Chungseon ascended the throne, he was the first to be summoned, and received honors most generous—yet the Lay Buddhist found no joy in this, and pressed ever more urgently to depart, until he was granted retirement as Vice Minister of密直 and Scholar of the Hall. His household discipline was exemplary, his sons all renowned, and his youngest bore such rectitude and noble character that he became a great minister of the realm. Alas—can such distinction arise without talent? Can one abandon rank and station without virtue? Can the Way, if not rooted in one's person, yet move the ears of three reigns? Can teachings, if not practiced within the home, yet bear fruit through generations?

    Seeing the truth of his deeds manifest thus, though one had not beheld his entire collection, what is rooted in his heart and revealed in his words could still be known. Alas, I am now doubly convinced: he who possesses virtue must surely possess speech.

    Written on the third day after the winter solstice, nineteenth year of至正.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Dongang居士 (the Lay Buddhist Dongang) was a title of respect for Lee Geung (1338-1392), a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar and statesman of Goryeo.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three reigns' refers to Kings Chunggyeong, Chungnyeol, and Chungseon—monarchs under whom Lee Geung served.
  - key: ''
    value: Dutasan Mountain was a retreat for scholars and Buddhist practitioners; withdrawal there symbolized rejection of worldly office.
